the G1, one of our first

00:15:48.120 --> 00:15:50.390
releases, back in 2009.

00:15:50.390 --> 00:15:51.890
Technically it wasn't our
first release, that was

00:15:51.890 --> 00:15:54.690
Android 1.0, but it looked
pretty much the same.

00:15:54.690 --> 00:15:57.710
And if you're using Android
today, it should be familiar,

00:15:57.710 --> 00:16:00.430
you have your App Launcher, you
have your Icon Drawer, and

00:16:00.430 --> 00:16:03.270
we opened up a Settings App
here just as a demo.

00:16:03.270 --> 00:16:05.110
And you can see that there's
this little drawer you had to

00:16:05.110 --> 00:16:07.280
pull up manually, we have this
big, bulky search widget on

00:16:07.280 --> 00:16:08.950
the desktop.

00:16:08.950 --> 00:16:11.730
The Settings App, you sort of
get this sort of ugly wall of

00:16:11.730 --> 00:16:15.900
text with these down chevrons
that go somewhere down, I'm

00:16:15.900 --> 00:16:18.190
not sure where Down means.

00:16:18.190 --> 00:16:20.420
And that was Android.

00:16:20.420 --> 00:16:23.050
Sort of a rough start,
but we'll get there.

00:16:23.050 --> 00:16:24.580
So let's move forward
one version.

00:16:24.580 --> 00:16:28.900
This is Donut now, released just
a short time later, and

00:16:28.900 --> 00:16:30.410
not much has actually changed.

00:16:30.410 --> 00:16:32.750
We've gone and cleaned up that
big, bulky search widget, it's

00:16:32.750 --> 00:16:36.260
a little more streamlined now,
but not too many other changes

00:16:36.260 --> 00:16:38.940
there that are really notable,
at least as far

00:16:38.940 --> 00:16:40.770
as the UI is concerned.

00:16:40.770 --> 00:16:43.310
So then we're going to take
one more step forward to

00:16:43.310 --> 00:16:45.270
Android 2.0, that's Eclair.

00:16:45.270 --> 00:16:47.630
And this release is notable
because this is the one that

00:16:47.630 --> 00:16:49.970
came out with the
Motorola Droid.

00:16:49.970 --> 00:16:54.020
We did a lot of work to go and
clean up the UI here, so icons

00:16:54.020 --> 00:16:57.470
are a little bit more
streamlined, the Settings App

00:16:57.470 --> 00:17:00.180
is actually not a giant wall of
text, we've gotten rid of

00:17:00.180 --> 00:17:02.210
those confusing chevrons.

00:17:02.210 --> 00:17:03.930
The App Launcher is still more
or less the same thing,

00:17:03.930 --> 00:17:06.660
though, you have the store you
pull up manually, some carbon

00:17:06.660 --> 00:17:11.549
fiber texter there in the
background, and that was what

00:17:11.549 --> 00:17:14.040
we released there
with the Droid.

00:17:14.040 --> 00:17:16.200
Take one more step forward
here, and get to Froyo,

00:17:16.200 --> 00:17:17.750
Version 2.2.

00:17:17.750 --> 00:17:21.430
And this one is probably where
you see the most changes.

00:17:21.430 --> 00:17:24.640
We've actually gone and removed
the drawer that you

00:17:24.640 --> 00:17:27.170
actually had to go and swipe
up with an App Launcher

00:17:27.170 --> 00:17:31.598
button, added a set of Quick
Actions there at the bottom to

00:17:31.598 --> 00:17:33.610
go and pull up the phone and the
browser, which are pretty

00:17:33.610 --> 00:17:35.920
common actions on a smartphone,
and we added

00:17:35.920 --> 00:17:38.130
System-wide Search, so you'll
notice that Search widget's

00:17:38.130 --> 00:17:41.190
changed just a little
bit, too.

00:17:41.190 --> 00:17:43.520
Settings App still looks
more or less the same.

00:17:43.520 --> 00:17:47.460
You still have this gray bar at
the top with this App Name,

00:17:47.460 --> 00:17:49.340
navigation hasn't
changed much.

00:17:49.340 --> 00:17:53.285
And that was probably, to date,
the biggest change to

00:17:53.285 --> 00:17:56.000
the Android UI we've seen.

00:17:56.000 --> 00:17:58.420
And then one last step forward,
which was Android

00:17:58.420 --> 00:17:59.760
2.3, Gingerbread.

00:17:59.760 --> 00:18:02.465
And you'll notice the biggest
change here is we sort of made

00:18:02.465 --> 00:18:05.630
the UI a little bit darker, this
little widget we added on

00:18:05.630 --> 00:18:08.030
the desktop to sort of give
you a tutorial has changed

00:18:08.030 --> 00:18:11.140
just slightly, made it a little
darker, the Quick

00:18:11.140 --> 00:18:14.710
Actions at the bottom have
changed, the Notification Bar

00:18:14.710 --> 00:18:16.440
has changed.

00:18:16.440 --> 00:18:19.760
Still the same Settings App,
still the same Launcher,

00:18:19.760 --> 00:18:21.060
pretty much.

00:18:21.060 --> 00:18:23.900
And so that was our previous
releases of Android.

00:18:23.900 --> 00:18:28.350
That's where we've come to
up until fairly recently.

00:18:28.350 --> 00:18:31.140
So when we were building
Honeycomb, we took a step back

00:18:31.140 --> 00:18:35.120
and said, well, we've had the
same look since the beginning.

00:18:35.120 --> 00:18:36.470
What can we change?

00:18:36.470 --> 00:18:39.910
There's a lot of wasted screen
real estate with buttons, a

00:18:39.910 --> 00:18:45.370
lot of space taken up by these
big, bulky text fields, and it

00:18:45.370 --> 00:18:48.420
sort of felt inspired
by a desktop OS.

00:18:48.420 --> 00:18:51.460
And you have this magical pane
of glass in front of you, and

00:18:51.460 --> 00:18:52.460
there's so much more
you can do.

00:18:52.460 --> 00:18:54.310
It can be this tactile
experience.

00:18:54.310 --> 00:18:56.820
You can go and get rid of all
these desktop metaphors and

00:18:56.820 --> 00:18:59.780
sort of come up with a
brand new experience.

00:18:59.780 --> 00:19:02.570
And, like I said, we haven't
really changed that much.

00:19:02.570 --> 00:19:04.980
There was that change with 1.5,
but it was more of an

00:19:04.980 --> 00:19:08.020
incremental change, it wasn't
really revolutionary.

00:19:08.020 --> 00:19:10.760
We also noticed that there's
a lot of inconsistency.

00:19:10.760 --> 00:19:13.690
Android, of course, allows
device manufacturers to go and

00:19:13.690 --> 00:19:16.920
modify the OS, to go and
edit and to add some

00:19:16.920 --> 00:19:18.370
distinctiveness to it.

00:19:18.370 --> 00:19:21.450
But the feedback we heard from
a lot of designers was if you

00:19:21.450 --> 00:19:23.960
go and change the text color,
if you change the selection

00:19:23.960 --> 00:19:26.900
color, if you change the way a
List View behaves, the way

00:19:26.900 --> 00:19:29.670
Overscroller works, and you're
really going for that picture

00:19:29.670 --> 00:19:32.490
perfect UI, when these things
change out from under you, it

00:19:32.490 --> 00:19:34.810
makes it hard to go and make
your app look beautiful.

00:19:34.810 --> 00:19:39.350
So we took all this feedback,
and we put it together and we

00:19:39.350 --> 00:19:42.500
got to what we call Holo,
our holographic UI.

00:19:42.500 --> 00:19:45.280
So going back to 2.3 here,
let's take one more step

00:19:45.280 --> 00:19:47.910
forward, and this is the
face of Android today.

00:19:47.910 --> 00:19:49.630
Still the same metaphors you're
sort of familiar with

00:19:49.630 --> 00:19:51.530
as far as having an App
Launcher, right?

00:19:51.530 --> 00:19:54.210
I mean, there hasn't been that
much that's changed there.

00:19:54.210 --> 00:19:58.370
But the bigger changes are
a little more subtle.

00:19:58.370 --> 00:20:01.330
If you look at the Search
Widget, you'll notice it's a

00:20:01.330 --> 00:20:04.110
lot more minimalist. We've added
these blue futuristic

00:20:04.110 --> 00:20:06.240
highlights everywhere, organized
the Settings App

00:20:06.240 --> 00:20:08.730
finally so it actually makes
a little bit more sense to

00:20:08.730 --> 00:20:09.890
scroll through.

00:20:09.890 --> 00:20:11.910
And then there's also this space
at the top of the screen

00:20:11.910 --> 00:20:14.460
that's reserved for what
we call the action bar.

00:20:14.460 --> 00:20:16.090
And we'll go into that in a bit
more detail, but that's

00:20:16.090 --> 00:20:17.510
actually pretty important.

00:20:17.510 --> 00:20:19.840
So this is Holo.

00:20:19.840 --> 00:20:22.410
One release for all devices,
whether or not it's a tablet

00:20:22.410 --> 00:20:23.910
or a phone.

00:20:23.910 --> 00:20:26.180
And we really have gone through
and we've taken a look

00:20:26.180 --> 00:20:28.350
at everything in the phone,
whether or not it's how a

00:20:28.350 --> 00:20:30.780
dialog appears, how a List View
behaves, how you scroll

00:20:30.780 --> 00:20:34.080
through your media, and asked
ourselves what assumptions

00:20:34.080 --> 00:20:36.520
we've been making
for this design.

00:20:36.520 --> 00:20:40.020
And this goes all the way down
to the Widget Toolkit.

00:20:40.020 --> 00:20:43.610
So this is the selection of most
of the controls that come

00:20:43.610 --> 00:20:47.190
with the SDK, of course,
you can add more.

00:20:47.190 --> 00:20:51.090
The big one there is probably
the Text Input Fields, and you

00:20:51.090 --> 00:20:53.150
can actually barely see
them on the screen.

00:20:53.150 --> 00:20:55.510
It's sort of up there in the
upper right, and it's actually

00:20:55.510 --> 00:20:56.890
just a line.

00:20:56.890 --> 00:20:59.600
And I'll show you a screen shot
of that in a moment, but

00:20:59.600 --> 00:21:02.156
actually, let's go right
there right now.

00:21:02.156 --> 00:21:04.690
So on the left is the Email App
in Gingerbread, and on the

00:21:04.690 --> 00:21:06.465
right is the Email
App in Honeycomb

00:21:06.465 --> 00:21:07.970
and Ice Cream Sandwich.

00:21:07.970 --> 00:21:11.470
And you'll notice, we've really
just reduced it to a

00:21:11.470 --> 00:21:12.630
sheet of paper.

00:21:12.630 --> 00:21:15.180
Of course, you still need your
Text Fields to address the

00:21:15.180 --> 00:21:17.930
email, give it a subject,
actually compose.

00:21:17.930 --> 00:21:19.910
But the UI sort of fades into
the background and brings your

00:21:19.910 --> 00:21:22.810
content front and center so the
users can focus on their

00:21:22.810 --> 00:21:25.450
creativity and not on what
their phone is trying to

00:21:25.450 --> 00:21:28.230
impose as far as the
UI's concerned.

00:21:28.230 --> 00:21:33.150
So we basically have three
design principles that

00:21:33.150 --> 00:21:34.360
underlie Holo.

00:21:34.360 --> 00:21:38.740
And we wanted a UI that felt
enchanting, that simplified

00:21:38.740 --> 00:21:41.610
users' lives, and that made
them feel amazing and

00:21:41.610 --> 00:21:43.520
empowered because of that.

00:21:43.520 --> 00:21:46.270
So let's talk about those in a
little bit more detail, give

00:21:46.270 --> 00:21:48.060
you a quick tour through
the some of the

00:21:48.060 --> 00:21:50.330
design highlights here.

00:21:50.330 --> 00:21:53.650
So we wanted to be delightful.

00:21:53.650 --> 00:21:55.840
There's lots of visual
flourishes sprinkled

00:21:55.840 --> 00:21:57.070
throughout the OS.

00:21:57.070 --> 00:21:59.895
When you're scrolling left or
right on the Home Screen and

00:21:59.895 --> 00:22:02.830
you hit one end of the screen,
this pane of light will sort

00:22:02.830 --> 00:22:05.030
of pop out from the screen
for just a second.

00:22:05.030 --> 00:22:07.700
It's a very subtle effect, but
it gives your phone a bit of

00:22:07.700 --> 00:22:10.280
personality, makes it feel a bit
more fun, makes you feel

00:22:10.280 --> 00:22:11.540
like it has a bit more
substance, that you're

00:22:11.540 --> 00:22:15.040
actually working with this
physical interface

00:22:15.040 --> 00:22:17.320
inside of the phone.

00:22:17.320 --> 00:22:21.350
Sort of extending from that idea
of a physical interface,

00:22:21.350 --> 00:22:24.640
objects behave as actual objects
rather than buttons.

00:22:24.640 --> 00:22:26.750
If you have an icon and you
drop it on top of another

00:22:26.750 --> 00:22:28.380
icon, what do you expect
should happen?

00:22:28.380 --> 00:22:29.330
They should stack.

00:22:29.330 --> 00:22:31.260
Well, that's exactly
what happens.

00:22:31.260 --> 00:22:34.770
And so little things like
that are found all

00:22:34.770 --> 00:22:38.070
throughout the OS.

00:22:38.070 --> 00:22:40.040
Personalization has always
been an important part of

00:22:40.040 --> 00:22:41.040
Android, it still is.

00:22:41.040 --> 00:22:43.240
We want the user to feel like
their phone belongs to them,

00:22:43.240 --> 00:22:45.550
so of course, it starts with
things like setting your

00:22:45.550 --> 00:22:48.440
background, being able to go
and adjust the behavior of

00:22:48.440 --> 00:22:50.340
your phone, add widgets
everywhere,

00:22:50.340 --> 00:22:52.400
make the phone yours.

00:22:52.400 --> 00:22:55.490
On the other hand, the phone
will get to know you and

00:22:55.490 --> 00:22:57.160
personalize itself
automatically.

00:22:57.160 --> 00:22:59.800
So as you're browsing around
the web, and say you go and

00:22:59.800 --> 00:23:01.200
visit Wikipedia a lot.

00:23:01.200 --> 00:23:03.700
Your phone will, of course,
save that in its local

00:23:03.700 --> 00:23:06.280
history, and then later on, when
you go and try and do a

00:23:06.280 --> 00:23:09.260
system-wide search, it'll check
that history and start

00:23:09.260 --> 00:23:11.510
adding auto-complete suggestions
for Wikipedia,

00:23:11.510 --> 00:23:12.760
even though you're not
in the browser.

00:23:16.740 --> 00:23:20.260
So the next topic there,
simplifying your life.

00:23:23.240 --> 00:23:24.550
Actually, let's move to
the next screen here.

00:23:24.550 --> 00:23:27.920
So first things first, we want
to go and keep the dialogues

00:23:27.920 --> 00:23:29.820
nice and simple, wizards
nice and simple.

00:23:29.820 --> 00:23:31.780
When you first turn your
phone on, we have this

00:23:31.780 --> 00:23:32.860
initial setup process.

00:23:32.860 --> 00:23:36.542
So as an example here, one of
the screens asks you to go and

00:23:36.542 --> 00:23:38.010
set up a Google account.

00:23:38.010 --> 00:23:40.580
And we keep the text there
brief, and when you actually

00:23:40.580 --> 00:23:42.930
go to sign up for the account,
it's just a one-page

00:23:42.930 --> 00:23:44.220
form you fill out.

00:23:44.220 --> 00:23:46.670
Just as an example there, but
throughout the system, we've

00:23:46.670 --> 00:23:48.490
gone and reevaluated all of our
dialogs, trying to figure

00:23:48.490 --> 00:23:52.340
out where we were being too
verbose, not saying enough,

00:23:52.340 --> 00:23:55.590
and kept it basically the bare
minimum we could while still

00:23:55.590 --> 00:23:58.200
being informative.

00:23:58.200 --> 00:24:02.740
Pictures and these graphical
UIs are a big part of Holo.

00:24:02.740 --> 00:24:06.150
We sort of call this like a
Magazine UI, so big, high

00:24:06.150 --> 00:24:08.025
resolution, vibrant pictures
right there in

00:24:08.025 --> 00:24:09.180
front of your screen.

00:24:09.180 --> 00:24:10.930
And so this is the Dialer App.

00:24:10.930 --> 00:24:12.990
When you launched Dialer App in
the past, it used to give

00:24:12.990 --> 00:24:15.310
you this whole list view of
contacts, and you could scroll

00:24:15.310 --> 00:24:16.800
through, and eventually,
you'd find who

00:24:16.800 --> 00:24:17.730
you're looking through.

00:24:17.730 --> 00:24:19.790
You could star people, add
them to the Quick List.

00:24:19.790 --> 00:24:22.700
We found that it makes it a lot
quicker if you just have a

00:24:22.700 --> 00:24:23.420
picture right there.

00:24:23.420 --> 00:24:26.116
If I want to call Mattias and I
open my phone, well there he

00:24:26.116 --> 00:24:27.592
is in the upper left hand
corner where I can

00:24:27.592 --> 00:24:27.725
just click on him.

00:24:27.725 --> 00:24:29.810
I don't actually have to go
through and read everything.

00:24:29.810 --> 00:24:31.760
And so pictures are a lot
faster than words.

00:24:31.760 --> 00:24:34.340
We try and use these high
resolution images throughout

00:24:34.340 --> 00:24:37.530
the UI whenever we can.

00:24:37.530 --> 00:24:39.870
We also try and do the right
thing automatically.

00:24:39.870 --> 00:24:43.080
So we've added a feature in
Android Four, Ice Cream

00:24:43.080 --> 00:24:45.090
Sandwich, called Android Beam.

00:24:45.090 --> 00:24:47.010
And when you take two phones and
you hold them next to each

00:24:47.010 --> 00:24:49.470
other, if they have an NFT
antenna, they'll detect that

00:24:49.470 --> 00:24:50.840
the other phone is
in proximity and

00:24:50.840 --> 00:24:51.700
enter the Share Mode.

00:24:51.700 --> 00:24:54.010
You can then go and tap on
whatever content is on your

00:24:54.010 --> 00:24:57.150
screen, and it'll send it
over to the other phone.

00:24:57.150 --> 00:25:00.620
So we're using this contact
sensitivity to go and just

00:25:00.620 --> 00:25:03.380
automatically throw the user
into the Share Mode so that

00:25:03.380 --> 00:25:05.770
the action they most likely want
to perform, since they've

00:25:05.770 --> 00:25:08.000
put their phones next
to another phone, is

00:25:08.000 --> 00:25:10.110
just one tap away.

00:25:10.110 --> 00:25:12.340
Of course, you still want to
leave that final act up to the

00:25:12.340 --> 00:25:15.120
user and not do everything for
them, but just get them into

00:25:15.120 --> 00:25:19.860
the right position so that
they're ready to do that.

00:25:19.860 --> 00:25:21.620
Navigation is, of course,
important.

00:25:21.620 --> 00:25:25.040
We've always had this concept
of a Back button on Android.

00:25:25.040 --> 00:25:27.520
We've got and extended that a
bit more with the Action Bar.

00:25:27.520 --> 00:25:30.480
I'll go into that in a bit more
detail in a moment here.

00:25:30.480 --> 00:25:33.820
Also, we've gone and taken the
most commonly used actions and

00:25:33.820 --> 00:25:35.850
pulled them out of
the Menu Bar.

00:25:35.850 --> 00:25:37.620
In fact, the Menu Bar is
pretty much [INAUDIBLE]

00:25:37.620 --> 00:25:39.290
at this point.

00:25:39.290 --> 00:25:42.610
If you target your app for
Android Three or above, so

00:25:42.610 --> 00:25:45.040
anyone running Holo, we actually
remove the Menu

00:25:45.040 --> 00:25:48.250
button from the screen and
place all of the old Menu

00:25:48.250 --> 00:25:50.080
commands up in this
Action Bar.

00:25:50.080 --> 00:25:52.850
And as a developer, you could
pick whether or not something

00:25:52.850 --> 00:25:56.090
should be displayed right there,
one click away, at the

00:25:56.090 --> 00:25:58.360
top of the Action Bar, or we
still do have an Overflow Menu

00:25:58.360 --> 00:26:00.820
where you can hide the less
commonly used actions.

00:26:00.820 --> 00:26:03.250
But the really important actions
should be right there,

00:26:03.250 --> 00:26:05.930
one click away at all times, and
your phone should go and

00:26:05.930 --> 00:26:08.660
adjust its UI to what
you're doing so

00:26:08.660 --> 00:26:10.270
those are always there.

00:26:10.270 --> 00:26:11.890
And I'll give you some more
examples of that in a moment.

00:26:17.690 --> 00:26:21.120
Also going off of navigation,
consistency is important.

00:26:21.120 --> 00:26:23.470
The Action Bar that we've added
does a lot towards that.

00:26:23.470 --> 00:26:26.030
So we have examples here
from Maps, Inbox,

00:26:26.030 --> 00:26:27.430
and the Gallery App.

00:26:27.430 --> 00:26:29.870
And you'll notice that even
though they are very different

00:26:29.870 --> 00:26:31.580
apps, they look different.

00:26:31.580 --> 00:26:33.460
A Map View looks a lot different
than a Gallery View

00:26:33.460 --> 00:26:35.620
looks a lot different
than your email.

00:26:35.620 --> 00:26:37.940
The navigation looks the same
in all of those, and that's

00:26:37.940 --> 00:26:38.730
intentional.

00:26:38.730 --> 00:26:40.400
And we've provided the tools
to go and do that for app

00:26:40.400 --> 00:26:42.210
developers anywhere
in the system.

00:26:42.210 --> 00:26:45.020
And if you're a long-time
Android user, notifications

00:26:45.020 --> 00:26:47.220
are of course a very important
part of that experience, we've

00:26:47.220 --> 00:26:49.080
had that since the beginning.

00:26:49.080 --> 00:26:52.280
But just to go and reiterate,
we want to go and make sure

00:26:52.280 --> 00:26:56.410
that whenever there's an
important event that occurs,

00:26:56.410 --> 00:26:59.160
of course, since it's important,
you want to let the

00:26:59.160 --> 00:27:02.390
user know, but make sure that
you only interrupt them if

00:27:02.390 --> 00:27:03.490
it's important.

00:27:03.490 --> 00:27:07.190
And if it's not important, we
go and tuck it away so that

00:27:07.190 --> 00:27:10.430
users can respond to that
notification later.

00:27:10.430 --> 00:27:13.030
So we bring things up, give them
a chance to respond, and

00:27:13.030 --> 00:27:15.230
then let them deal with things
on their own time, so you

00:27:15.230 --> 00:27:16.970
don't get any big, bulky dialogs
that come up and stop

00:27:16.970 --> 00:27:19.620
the user from what they're
trying to do.

00:27:19.620 --> 00:27:21.750
So on this last part about
empowering the user and making

00:27:21.750 --> 00:27:26.030
them feel amazing, we've added
lots of gestures throughout

00:27:26.030 --> 00:27:28.290
the system that let
you go and--

00:27:28.290 --> 00:27:30.510
basically, they're tricks that
let the user pull something

00:27:30.510 --> 00:27:35.410
off with some gesture, some
action, and do it without

00:27:35.410 --> 00:27:36.090
having to push a button.

00:27:36.090 --> 00:27:39.160
We're trying to remove as many
buttons from the UI as we can.

00:27:39.160 --> 00:27:44.390
And gestures are always a little
tricky because you can

00:27:44.390 --> 00:27:46.060
put up a little tool tip and
tell them, but most of the

00:27:46.060 --> 00:27:47.440
time, they're not pushing
something

00:27:47.440 --> 00:27:48.570
that's labeled there.

00:27:48.570 --> 00:27:50.660
So once you go and perform some
gesture, we want to make

00:27:50.660 --> 00:27:52.850
sure that it works throughout
the system.

00:27:52.850 --> 00:27:54.990
Once you've learned in Gmail
that you can swipe left and

00:27:54.990 --> 00:27:57.290
right between your email
messages, you'll discover oh,

00:27:57.290 --> 00:27:59.850
you can do the same thing in
Google Play, you can swipe

00:27:59.850 --> 00:28:02.250
left to right between categories
in the App Store.

00:28:02.250 --> 00:28:05.020
You can also go into the Google
Plus App and do the

00:28:05.020 --> 00:28:07.390
same thing and switch
between your own

00:28:07.390 --> 00:28:11.540
circles and people nearby.

00:28:11.540 --> 00:28:14.260
Dialogs, we've gone and cleaned
those up again, made

00:28:14.260 --> 00:28:15.730
sure that they're
actually useful.

00:28:15.730 --> 00:28:17.580
Rather than just saying that
there's an error that's

00:28:17.580 --> 00:28:19.760
occurred and taking you onto the
Support Page, we try and

00:28:19.760 --> 00:28:21.790
give you the text you need to
make sure you can respond to

00:28:21.790 --> 00:28:26.160
it and actually resolve
the situation.

00:28:26.160 --> 00:28:29.100
There's little bits of visual
encouragement sprinkled

00:28:29.100 --> 00:28:29.740
throughout the system.

00:28:29.740 --> 00:28:32.390
So as you're going and dragging
icons around, we

00:28:32.390 --> 00:28:37.650
overlay this grid and put this
little shadow of the icon that

00:28:37.650 --> 00:28:40.170
sort of jumps around as you
drag your icons around.

00:28:40.170 --> 00:28:43.470
So even if you've never used
an Android device before,

00:28:43.470 --> 00:28:45.110
you'll immediately know that
these devices are going to go

00:28:45.110 --> 00:28:46.360
and snap to a grid.

00:28:48.530 --> 00:28:51.630
And finally, this is less of
a UI issue and more of a

00:28:51.630 --> 00:28:55.260
functionality issue, but apps
should be smart, and they

00:28:55.260 --> 00:28:56.820
should do the heavy lifting
for the user.

00:28:56.820 --> 00:28:59.340
If you have a smartphone in
your pocket, it should be

00:28:59.340 --> 00:29:00.280
smart, right?

00:29:00.280 --> 00:29:02.000
So it's little things.

00:29:02.000 --> 00:29:03.560
If you're in the Camera App,
you should automatically

00:29:03.560 --> 00:29:04.750
adjust white balance,
you should

00:29:04.750 --> 00:29:06.420
automatically set focal points.

00:29:06.420 --> 00:29:08.440
Sure, give the users a way to
go and set it if they want,

00:29:08.440 --> 00:29:10.060
but by default, you should
just go and do everything

00:29:10.060 --> 00:29:11.430
automatically.

00:29:11.430 --> 00:29:13.110
Which also gets to the next
point here, which is you

00:29:13.110 --> 00:29:16.050
should make the important things
fast. Again, if you're

00:29:16.050 --> 00:29:17.270
in the Camera App, the
most important

00:29:17.270 --> 00:29:18.640
thing is taking a picture.

00:29:18.640 --> 00:29:20.780
If you press that Shutter
button, you should take a

00:29:20.780 --> 00:29:22.090
picture immediately.

00:29:22.090 --> 00:29:24.920
So we've even gone so far as
to go and add zero-second

00:29:24.920 --> 00:29:25.840
shutter lags.

00:29:25.840 --> 00:29:27.940
From the moment you press that
button, the photo is

00:29:27.940 --> 00:29:30.080
immediately saved to disk and
there's no delay while you're

00:29:30.080 --> 00:29:32.070
waiting for the shutter to fire
and for it to find the

00:29:32.070 --> 00:29:33.250
focal point.

00:29:33.250 --> 00:29:35.150
It's instant.

00:29:35.150 --> 00:29:37.150
So as an Android app developer,
what does all of

00:29:37.150 --> 00:29:38.970
this mean to you?

00:29:38.970 --> 00:29:43.450
So we've gone and put together
a collection of design

00:29:43.450 --> 00:29:45.390
patterns that you can use.

00:29:45.390 --> 00:29:47.280
And the most important one, if
you haven't heard me mention

00:29:47.280 --> 00:29:49.720
it a dozen times already,
is the Action bar.

00:29:49.720 --> 00:29:53.970
This is the roughly 50 pixels,
I can't remember the exact

00:29:53.970 --> 00:29:56.480
number, of space at the top of
your screen that's reserved

00:29:56.480 --> 00:29:59.280
for the most important
navigational elements.

00:29:59.280 --> 00:30:01.190
And it's broken up into
three sections.

00:30:01.190 --> 00:30:04.010
You have an App icon, which
tells you where you are.

00:30:04.010 --> 00:30:06.880
Typically, this is going to be
your own application's icon,

00:30:06.880 --> 00:30:08.890
but you can change it, if you're
in a document, make it

00:30:08.890 --> 00:30:11.990
look like you're docked,
things like that.

00:30:11.990 --> 00:30:15.810
You have View Details, this is
things like navigational tabs.

00:30:15.810 --> 00:30:17.900
And then you have your Action
buttons, which tell the user

00:30:17.900 --> 00:30:19.160
what they can do.

00:30:19.160 --> 00:30:22.110
And this can either be the
Overflow menu, where you put

00:30:22.110 --> 00:30:26.400
the less commonly used actions,
like I said, you can

00:30:26.400 --> 00:30:28.800
bring those actions front and
center, just place them there.

00:30:28.800 --> 00:30:32.510
You can even add custom views,
things like search widgets.

00:30:32.510 --> 00:30:35.900
Basically, anything the user
wants to do commonly should be

00:30:35.900 --> 00:30:37.910
part of that Action Bar.

00:30:37.910 --> 00:30:38.580
It's also contextual.

00:30:38.580 --> 00:30:41.510
So as you start making
selections, we actually will

00:30:41.510 --> 00:30:44.310
swap that Action bar out, flip
it around, and give you a

00:30:44.310 --> 00:30:45.770
completely different
set of commands.

00:30:45.770 --> 00:30:48.420
If you're in email, normally the
first thing you'd want to

00:30:48.420 --> 00:30:50.380
do is compose a new message.

00:30:50.380 --> 00:30:52.390
Once you start selecting
messages, it's not likely

00:30:52.390 --> 00:30:53.900
that's what you want
to do anymore.

00:30:53.900 --> 00:30:55.710
Most likely what you want to
do is something related to

00:30:55.710 --> 00:30:56.390
organization.

00:30:56.390 --> 00:30:57.950
You're going to want to archive
your messages, or

00:30:57.950 --> 00:31:00.510
you're going to want to go and
maybe mass delete them if

00:31:00.510 --> 00:31:03.510
they're all spam,
Heaven forbid.

00:31:03.510 --> 00:31:06.750
So as soon as you go and enter
this different mode, the phone

00:31:06.750 --> 00:31:10.760
will go and adapt and place you
in the right context for

00:31:10.760 --> 00:31:12.520
whatever it is that you're
most likely to

00:31:12.520 --> 00:31:15.240
going to want to do.

00:31:15.240 --> 00:31:15.880
Navigation.

00:31:15.880 --> 00:31:19.450
I mentioned that there is this
Back button, and then we've

00:31:19.450 --> 00:31:22.850
added an initial Back command
up to the Action bar.

00:31:22.850 --> 00:31:25.160
So the Back button, which
has been there since the

00:31:25.160 --> 00:31:28.100
beginning, provides temporal
back navigation.

00:31:28.100 --> 00:31:30.860
So if I'm in my web browser and
I click a link that takes

00:31:30.860 --> 00:31:34.500
me to the Google Play Store,
when I click Back, it's going

00:31:34.500 --> 00:31:36.740
to take me back into the
browser, because that's the

00:31:36.740 --> 00:31:39.370
last thing I did as far
as my sequence of

00:31:39.370 --> 00:31:40.690
events on the phone.

00:31:40.690 --> 00:31:42.550
But what we discovered is
sometimes users actually want

00:31:42.550 --> 00:31:45.330
to go and once they navigate
into that other app, they want

00:31:45.330 --> 00:31:47.140
to go and explore more there.

00:31:47.140 --> 00:31:49.700
They want to get back to the
home page of that app.

00:31:49.700 --> 00:31:52.990
And so the other Back button is
a hierarchical Back button.

00:31:52.990 --> 00:31:56.680
It'll take you back up within
the navigational tree of the

00:31:56.680 --> 00:31:58.110
current application.

00:31:58.110 --> 00:32:00.720
So we actually call it Up.

00:32:00.720 --> 00:32:02.590
So that's actually, if you think
of a tree, you're going

00:32:02.590 --> 00:32:04.200
back up to the root
of that tree.

00:32:04.200 --> 00:32:06.660
So if I'm in Google Play and I'm
in an App Detail page and

00:32:06.660 --> 00:32:10.810
I click Up, it'll start taking
me back to the Google Play

00:32:10.810 --> 00:32:12.690
main screen.

00:32:12.690 --> 00:32:15.610
And so that's a really important
navigational pattern

00:32:15.610 --> 00:32:18.040
that you'll find all throughout
Android now, and

00:32:18.040 --> 00:32:19.890
it's really important to go and
make sure your apps are

00:32:19.890 --> 00:32:20.420
updated to go [INAUDIBLE]

00:32:20.420 --> 00:32:22.010
of that.

00:32:22.010 --> 00:32:24.570
Multiple pane layouts are
important, because again, we

00:32:24.570 --> 00:32:27.930
have one release of Android
for tablets and phones.

00:32:27.930 --> 00:32:31.060
So this is sort of a pattern
people have been using in

00:32:31.060 --> 00:32:32.090
mobile apps since
the beginning.

00:32:32.090 --> 00:32:33.470
You have, say, your
Contacts App.

00:32:33.470 --> 00:32:35.030
You have this table of contents
that lists all of

00:32:35.030 --> 00:32:37.640
your contacts, you click on
somebody, and it'll take you

00:32:37.640 --> 00:32:39.030
into a Detail View.

00:32:39.030 --> 00:32:40.800
So what we've done is we've
broken that up into what we

00:32:40.800 --> 00:32:44.500
call fragments, so you can go
and lay them out side by side.

00:32:44.500 --> 00:32:47.230
So now, same views, you still
have that table of

00:32:47.230 --> 00:32:48.040
contents on the left.

00:32:48.040 --> 00:32:50.020
You still have your details on
the right, but you can go and

00:32:50.020 --> 00:32:52.370
stack them and rearrange them.

00:32:52.370 --> 00:32:53.940
And so this does two things.

00:32:53.940 --> 00:32:56.200
One, it's a really intuitive way
to go into the device as a

00:32:56.200 --> 00:32:58.930
user, and as an app developer,
it allows you

00:32:58.930 --> 00:32:59.830
to reuse your code.

00:32:59.830 --> 00:33:02.070
It's actually the exact same
code laying out that table of

00:33:02.070 --> 00:33:04.690
contents and displaying that
Detail View, we're just going

00:33:04.690 --> 00:33:05.965
in and rendering both of
them simultaneously.

00:33:08.510 --> 00:33:10.160
And there's a lot of options
are to go in and rearrange

00:33:10.160 --> 00:33:10.640
things, too.

00:33:10.640 --> 00:33:14.170
So you can go and of course,
place them side by side like I

00:33:14.170 --> 00:33:16.520
did in that example, or you can
go and stack them on the

00:33:16.520 --> 00:33:19.030
right, stack on the bottom, have
things slide in and out.

00:33:19.030 --> 00:33:22.370
We've added commands to
go and do animation.

00:33:22.370 --> 00:33:24.210
So there's lot of different ways
to go and compose your UI

00:33:24.210 --> 00:33:26.350
and make something that looks
really beautiful.

00:33:26.350 --> 00:33:27.820
And as an app designer,
it's up to you to

00:33:27.820 --> 00:33:28.910
figure out what works.

00:33:28.910 --> 00:33:31.070
We've given you the tools to
make sure that you can do it.

00:33:35.240 --> 00:33:38.050
I mentioned gestures already.

00:33:38.050 --> 00:33:39.190
Gestures are really important.

00:33:39.190 --> 00:33:42.830
We want to make sure that your
device feels like an actual

00:33:42.830 --> 00:33:44.740
environment that users
are interacting with.

00:33:44.740 --> 00:33:47.860
So we've actually documented a
whole set of common gestures,

00:33:47.860 --> 00:33:49.360
things that app developers will
want to go and integrate

00:33:49.360 --> 00:33:51.960
into their app, things like
double tapping to go and zoom

00:33:51.960 --> 00:33:55.550
in, being able to go and swipe
left and right to go and move

00:33:55.550 --> 00:33:56.410
between pages.

00:33:56.410 --> 00:33:57.930
Actually, that's what my
next slide will talk a

00:33:57.930 --> 00:33:59.390
little bit more, too.

00:33:59.390 --> 00:34:02.060
Drag and drop, we've added a
lot more APIs to go and let

00:34:02.060 --> 00:34:05.290
you go and take care of drag and
drop and move data between

00:34:05.290 --> 00:34:08.300
different fragments.

00:34:08.300 --> 00:34:08.989
Swipe Views.

00:34:08.989 --> 00:34:11.340
Like I said, you want to make
sure you can go and page

00:34:11.340 --> 00:34:13.840
through the different
parts of your app.

00:34:13.840 --> 00:34:17.380
We've added a class to our API
called View Pager that makes

00:34:17.380 --> 00:34:20.420
this really easy.

00:34:20.420 --> 00:34:24.389
And one last thing to talk about
here is, make sure your

00:34:24.389 --> 00:34:26.270
app feels like a pure
Android App.

00:34:26.270 --> 00:34:29.650
So I've taken a collection
here of UI elements from

00:34:29.650 --> 00:34:31.320
different mobile OS's.

00:34:31.320 --> 00:34:32.949
And functionally, they're
all the same.

00:34:32.949 --> 00:34:35.692
A button is a button, a check
box is a check box, a text

00:34:35.692 --> 00:34:37.340
field is a text field.

00:34:37.340 --> 00:34:39.429
But visually, they look
completely different.

00:34:39.429 --> 00:34:41.900
And if you're porting your app
over from one environment to

00:34:41.900 --> 00:34:46.080
another and you use the visual
elements from that other

